The paper proposes an extension of the Sparse Fourier Transform algorithm to higher dimensions, which is a topic related to signal processing and information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the computational complexity and tradeoff between signal SNR and computational complexity, which are topics related to numerical analysis and optimization, and thus cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also incorporates Neyman-Pearson detection, which is a statistical method, and thus cs.SI (Statistics) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the application of the proposed algorithm on short range ubiquitous radar signal processing, which is a topic related to machine learning and artificial intelligence, and thus cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
